l, class, and gender inequalities shape contestations over today’s uses and knowledges of urban nature. Drawing on fieldwork with gardeners, botanists, migrant workers, refugees, public officials, and nature enthusiasts while charting human and more-than-human worlds, Stoetzer offers a wide-ranging ethnographic portrait of Berlin’s postwar ecologies that reveals emergent futures in the margins of European cities. Brimming with stories that break down divides between environmental perspectives and the study of migration and racial politics, Berlin’s ruderal worlds help us rethink the space of nature and culture and the categories through which we make sense of urban life in inhospitable times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCity and town lifezGermanyzBerlinxHistory. 0aHuman ecologyzGermanyzBerlinxHistory. 0aNature and civilizationzGermanyzBerlin. 0aUrban ecology (Sociology)zGermanyzBerlinxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076691208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Comm 2022 Englishz978311099395008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Communication 2022z9783110994186oZDB-23-SEW40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478023203?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478023203423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478023203/original  a978-3-11-076691-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-099389-9